Nature of the Data¶

For our project, finding a public database of football data (both on field and off-field) with consistent and reliable data was the most essential part. Our data consists of two aspects: on field and off-field data. Both were obtained from different statistical data variables provided by FiveThirtyEight and Pro Football Reference. Nature of data is mainly categorical using official NFL player/team statistics from years 1977 to present, 1273 games(excluding NULL or inconsistent games). We chose 1977 to be the cutoff since data before 1977 was very unorganized and hard to keep track of with many teams moving cities and changing names.

Data Cleaning/Preprocessing¶

First data set obtained was the on-field data along with game-specific variable âIs_Evening_Gameâ which classifies if the game occurred before 1pm or not which we assumed could impact the performance of the players. For team name abbreviations, we followed the official NFL abbreviation and recorded the most recent name if any change was found. Next was team ELO data based on the ELO rating system that takes into account the relative strength of the opposition that can successfully gauge teamâs relative strengths and potentially enhance the predictive performance of our model by measuring the relative difficulty of the game for each team. We cross check our data set from years 1977 ~ present from other data sets for accuracy. This was merged with our previous dataset using the unique gameID(âDate formatâ + âhometeamâ).

Then, we incorporated player data from Pro Football Reference which was provided in a HTML format(multi-indexed) so we made a function to iterate and scrape data into a .csv file. Data was also cross checked with our existing data and fixed/updated team names and merged with gameID with our data set. The original game data was multi-indexed so we had to parse through each game and each team to retrieve the specific player we needed for modeling. For each game, we isolated the primary QB stats (if more than one QB plays in a game, the one with the higher total average will be chosen) and recorded a rolling average of the player statistics: fumbles_lost,two_point_conversion, and pass_long. We then calculated the difference (home team - away team) in a value of a given statistic (column) between the primary home team QB and away team QB. âVegas_Favorite_differenceâ was also calculated as one of the dependent variables for our data which measures the likelihood of a particular outcome. Positive values would favor the home team and negative values would favor the away team.

player_game_stats = pd.read_csv('nfl_pass_rush_receive_raw_data.csv')

def fix_game_id(game_id):
    old_abbrev = game_id[-3:]
    new_abbrev = abbrev_corrections[old_abbrev]
    return game_id[:-4] + new_abbrev

player_game_stats_fixed_abbev = player_game_stats.copy()
player_game_stats_fixed_abbev['game_id'] = player_game_stats_fixed_abbev['game_id'].apply(fix_game_id)

from datetime import datetime
time_date_strings = all_game_results_clean["Date"] + ' ' + all_game_results_clean["Time"]
time_date_objects = [datetime.strptime(x , '%Y-%m-%d %I:%M%p') for x in time_date_strings]
all_game_results_clean["time_date"] = time_date_objects

def get_game_id(winner, loser, location, time_date):
    if (location == "@"):
        home = loser
    else:
        home = winner
    strObj = str(time_date.isoformat()).split('T')[0]
    return ''.join((filter(lambda x: x not in ['-'], strObj))) + team_abbrev[home]
all_game_results_clean['game_id'] = all_game_results_clean.apply(lambda x : get_game_id(x['Winner/tie'], x['Loser/tie'], x['Unnamed: 5'], x['time_date']), axis = 1)

def fix_vegas_line(df):
    if df['home_team'] == df['Vegas_Favorite']:
        return abs(df['Vegas_Line'])
    else:
        return df['Vegas_Line']

quarterbacks['vegas_favorite'] = quarterbacks.apply(lambda x : fix_vegas_line(x), axis = 1)

def find_differences_qb(df, column):
    '''
    Finds the difference (home team - away  team) in value of a given statistic (column) between the primary home team
    qb and primary away team qb. Returns a Dataframe with the game id and the differences
    '''
    temp_dict = {}

    for index, row in quarterbacks.iterrows():
        if row['game_id'] in temp_dict:
            temp_dict[row['game_id']] += [[row['player_id'], int(row[column]), row['team'], row['home_team']]]
        else:
            temp_dict[row['game_id']] = [[row['player_id'], int(row[column]), row['team'], row['home_team']]]
    
    game_ids = []
    diffs = []
    
    for key in temp_dict:
        home_qbs = []
        away_qbs = []
        for v in temp_dict[key]:
            if v[2] == v[3]:
                home_qbs += [v]
            else:
                away_qbs += [v]
        diff = max(home_qbs, key = lambda x : x[1])[1] - max(away_qbs, key = lambda x : x[1])[1]
        game_ids += [key]
        diffs += [diff]
    
    temp_df = pd.DataFrame({'game_id': game_ids, column + '_diff (home - away)': diffs})
    return temp_df

In [143]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error

def OSR2(model, X_test, y_test, y_train):
    
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    SSE = np.sum((y_test - y_pred)**2)
    SST = np.sum((y_test - np.mean(y_train))**2)
                 
    return (1 - SSE/SST)

From the receiver operating characteristic curve (ROC CURVE) graph we can see that all models FPR and TPR in ROC Curve. AUC near to the 1 means it has a good measure of separability while Gradient Boosting with CV model has a higher area which is equal to 0.94 so we conclude that the Gradient Boosting with CV model is the most optimal model.
